sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_peaks
FROM peaks
WHERE run_id = 1;

SELECT COUNT(run_id) AS run_count
FROM chromatographic_runs
WHERE operator_id = 0;

SELECT run_date
FROM chromatographic_runs
ORDER BY run_date DESC;

SELECT retention_time
  FROM peaks
  WHERE peak_name = 'F';

SELECT operator_name
FROM operators
WHERE operator_id IN (
  SELECT DISTINCT operator_id
  FROM chromatographic_runs
);

SELECT AVG(confidence_level) AS average_confidence
FROM peak_assignments
WHERE category_id = 1;

SELECT run_name
FROM chromatographic_runs
WHERE run_status = 'in progress';

external_knowledge:
(operator_id = 1 refers to the head chemist); 
(method_name refers to the name of the chromatographic method used); 
(retention_time refers to the time a peak takes to reach its maximum value); 
(peaks are points of maximum value in a chromatographic run).

- In the context of chromatography, the total calibrated area percentage refers to the sum of the calibrated area percentages of all peaks in a run, which can be used to evaluate the overall performance of a chromatographic method; 
- The average retention time of a run is a measure of how long it takes for peaks to elute from the chromatographic column, which can affect the resolution and efficiency of the separation; 
- The ranking of runs by total calibrated area percentage and average retention time can help identify the most effective chromatographic methods and optimize the experimental conditions for future runs.

- Chromatographic runs involve separating and analyzing the components of a mixture; 
- Peak categories may refer to different types of compounds or components identified in the chromatographic process;
- Access events could be related to when the data from the chromatographic run was accessed or manipulated.

